Now, interestingly Matthew Hayden dashed off towards the dressing room, suggesting that Australia will bat again. Ponting has decided not to enforce the follow on. Interesting decision. Join us in a bit.

Rahul has a go: "The bowlers have bowled 80 overs. I don't understand this trend of modern captains not to enforce the follow on(after the 'Laxman Test' in 2001). Dravid did the same at the Oval. The most ridiculous was Ponting's decision to bat again in the Ashes test match when he has such a lead that he could have forfeited an innings!"

Ben chimes in: "I didn't think Ponting would enforce the follow-on - he only used 4 bowlers in the 1st innings; if he had been thinking of bowling twice he would have probably got Symonds (& maybe Clarke) to bowl a few to keep the quicks fresher."

Kong Howe from Malaysia writes in: "Relating to yesterday's discussion on Hussey's LBW dismissal: his bat was behind his pad and could, conceivably, have prevented the ball from hitting the stumps. Well, the authorities are well aware of this scenario:Law 36 Clause 2 (Interception of the Ball) states that "only the first interception is to be considered".

Not only does this make the decision simpler for the umpires but it would also discourage "hiding-the-bat" pseudo-strokes. Of course batsmen do this to reduce the exposure of their bats to edges.

If you go back to the roots of the Laws, it makes perfect sense. Otherwise, batsmen will simply place the bat in front of the stumps...One could argue, of course, that the bat is narrower than the width of the stumps. True, but at one point, a batsman showed up in a match with a bat that was as wide as the stumps - hence the hastily drafted law restricting the size of the bat."
